    "description": {
      "summary": "The griffin is a legendary creature combining the features of the king of beasts (lion) and the king of birds (eagle).",
      "full": "The griffin is a legendary creature combining the features of the king of beasts (lion) and the king of birds (eagle). Depicted with an eagle's head, beak, and wings, and a lion's body and tail, the griffin often has eagle's talons on its forelegs. In ancient mythology, griffins guarded treasures and sacred places, were sacred to Apollo, and their nests were said to contain gold. The griffin likely originated in the Ancient Near East over 5,000 years ago and spread through Scythian, Greek, and Roman cultures. A popular theory suggests griffins were inspired by Protoceratops fossils in gold-mining regions of ancient Scythia, which ancient peoples may have interpreted as the remains of these legendary guardians."
    },
